# Journal Viewer

### 🤖 Claude — [/claude](./claude/)

A desktop-ready journal app that pulls entries from a Notion database and displays them as a clean, page-by-page interface in your browser. Built with Claude and the Notion MCP integration.

---

## What it does

- Reads journal entries from a Notion database (date, mood, energy, priorities, reflections, notes, tomorrow)
- Displays them in a styled single-file HTML app you can open directly from your Desktop
- Navigate between entries with arrow keys or on-screen buttons
- No server, no install, no dependencies — just a file you open in a browser

---

## Files

| File | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `journal.html` | The journal viewer app |
| `sync-journal.ps1` | PowerShell helper that opens Claude to trigger a sync |

---

## Notion database structure

The viewer expects a Notion database with the following properties:

| Property | Type |
|----------|------|
| Entry | Title |
| Date | Date |
| Mood (1–10) | Number |
| Energy (1–10) | Number |
| Top 3 priorities | Text |
| Ideas / reflections | Text |
| Notes | Text |
| Tomorrow | Text |

---

## Setup

1. Download `journal.html` and `sync-journal.ps1` to your Desktop
2. Open `journal.html` in any browser — your entries will be visible immediately
3. Use ← → arrow keys or the on-screen buttons to move between entries

**If Windows blocks the PowerShell script**, open PowerShell once and run:
```powershell
Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser RemoteSigned
```

---

## Syncing new entries

The HTML file is statically generated — it doesn't connect to Notion automatically. To pull in new entries:

1. Right-click `sync-journal.ps1` → **Run with PowerShell**
2. Claude opens in your browser — type `sync my journal`
3. Claude fetches the latest entries from Notion and sends a new `journal.html`
4. Download it and overwrite the existing file on your Desktop

